article.description: The Seattle SuperSonics are a different team with Ray Allen leading the way _ maybe even the hottest team in the leag
article.headline: Allen scores 29 as Seattle wins fifth straight
article.linkText: Sonics stop T-Wolves win streak, stay on winning track
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics are a different team with Ray Allen leading the way -- maybe even the hottest team in the league.
 
Allen
Allen scored 29 points, Brent Barry had 19 and Rashard Lewis added 17 as the Seattle SuperSonics beat Minnesota 92-83 on Tuesday night, ending the Timberwolves' seven-game winning streak. The Sonics won their fifth straight and improved to 6-1 since Allen joined the team in a Feb. 20 swap for Gary Payton. "There's nothing special to our game plan except that we're playing hard, we're playing together and we're having fun," said Allen, who had nine rebounds and six assists. "Even the guys sitting on the bench, they look out on the floor and see how much fun we're having. Anytime you have that much fun, you just want to be a part of it," Allen said. Kevin Garnett scored 22 points and had 11 rebounds for Minnesota, but the Sonics held the All-Star game MVP to two points in the fourth quarter. Troy Hudson had 21 and Anthony Peeler 12 for the Timberwolves. "Over the last 20 games in terms of being aggressive, that's probably the worst we've played," Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "Guys played out of character. We were chasing the ball. We didn't run things the way we've been doing it." The Wolves have been one of the NBA's hottest teams over the past month, but five wins during their streak came at home. They opened a five-game Western Conference trip in Seattle by falling to 13-17 on the road this season. "I think this makes us the hottest team," Allen said. "We've beaten some good teams here. We went on the road and won. Now, we've got to go on the road and do the same thing. We won tonight and our emotions are high, but now we've got to settle in." Things were close through three quarters, but Allen and the Sonics' defense took over down the stretch. Seattle led 72-61 after Allen's jumper with 2:57 to play in the third, but Kendall Gill scored twice as Minnesota closed the period with an 8-3 burst. The Sonics made it 83-71 with 7:33 remaining when Jerome James capped a fastbreak with a dunk that forced a Minnesota timeout. Seattle had great ball movement, with Allen leading the play to Barry, who found James. Allen was just warming up, though. He found Barry for a 3-pointer that made it 88-74 with just under six minutes to go, then was under the basket for a rebound when Lewis missed a 3-point try with the 24-second clock ticking down. Allen took the ball to the backcourt to start over, then scored another basket despite Hudson smothering him and tugging at his jersey. That made it 90-74 with 4:01 remaining, and the Wolves got no closer than 91-83. Garnett said with Payton gone, the Sonics have to rely on each other more. "Instead of sitting back waiting for Gary to do everything, they're all taking responsibility for themselves," Garnett said. "Rashard is stepping up. They're just playing better as a team." Game notes
Garnett grew frustrated through the fourth quarter, receiving a technical foul after pushing Kevin Ollie with 2:33 to play. ... Seattle F Reggie Evans has collected at least eight rebounds in six of the last seven games, but didn't play most of the fourth quarter and finished with six. ... Minnesota has scored at least 100 points in 11 of its last 18 games.
